{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_guava_ver02/data/sn85042792/00332899946/1920123001/0094.xml":{"full_text":"toish to thank you for\nKl gour patronage in the \\B\nall past year anb fuislf you pros- |B\nIf parity anb happiness for the |B\nU Ncfu Dear. I\nW\\ A. E. ANDERSON\nB\\ Druggist Phone 130 K\n409 Main Street\n\u201cIf Our Name is on the\nLabel It\u2019s Right\u201d\nLocal and Personal\nE. O.\nBlecker Blecker, Chiropractors.\nGreat big Pre-Inventory Sale from\nJanuary 1 to 10, at the Boot Shop.\nMrs. J. H. Hubbard is spending the\nholidays with relatives at Colony,\nKansas.\nFor thirty days only, stamp photos,\nat clarin\u2019s Studio, fifty cents per\ndozen. Three positions.\nMiss Agnes Hagen returned Mon\nday night from her home at Florence\nwhere she visited over the holidays.\nJust arrived, another bunch of\nMargies, that big dance hit on Bruns\nwick record No. 2060. Phonograph\nShop\nMr. and Mrs. A. Fry returned Sat\nurday night from Iroquois where they\nspent Christmas with their son, R. K.\nFry and family.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles W. Estee of\nHecla, arrived Saturday evening for\nan Xmas visit at the home of their\nbrother, P. G. Estee.\nDon\u2019t let your subscription lapse to\nthe Register. The story we are about\nto publish is alone worth the price\nof a year\u2019s subscription.\nMrs. Roy Richardson of Sioux City,\nand Mrs. Muriel Herron of Salem,\nthis state, are holiday guests at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. P. G. Estee.\nMiss Kate Huetland, who is teach\ning school at Onida, spent Christmas\nat the home of Mr. and Mrs. E. B.\nFoster. Mrs. Foster is her sister.\nS. J. Kabrud left last week for\nFullerton, N. D., to spend the Christ\nmas holidays with his wife and fam\nily who are visiting relatives in that\ncity.\nS. R. and C. W. McClemans, accom\npanied by their little niece, Hazelie\nShort, spent. Christmas with their sis\nter, Jayne McClemans, at the home\nof Mrs. F. H. Farrankop.\nThe Misses Ruby Olson and Ber\nnadine Balbridge, who are attending\nschool at Monmouth college, Mon\nmouth, Illinois, are home for the holi\ndays visiting with their parents.\nMiss Rose Simonson of Chicago,\n111., Mrs. F. W. Dorn of Hendricks,\nMinn., and Miss Ruth Feenstra of Elk\nton, spent several days last week vis\niting their friend, Jayie Mc-\nClemans.\nGreat big Pre-Inventory Sale from\nJanuary 1 to 10, at the Boot Shop.\nOH BOY!\nCorner grocery\nSpecials for Monday and Tuesday\nSugar back to a pound\nRice, per pound\n5 lbs. Scoco lard compound 85 C\n3 bottles Eddy\u2019s blueing 15c\n2 cans Spotless Cleanser\nLarge can fancy sliced Pineapple.\nLarge package Oatmeal 32c\n9db. sack Oatmeal 59c\nCream Cheese, per lb 35c\n14 cans Northfield Milk (small). qq\n7 cans Northfield Milk (large). jy)\nSwift\u2019s Brisket Bacon, per ib....J()c\nLarge bottle Catsup 25c\nOnly 2 boxes Pearl White Soap\nleft, per box 100 bars $5.00\n2 cans Lewis\u2019 Lye 25c\nJonathan Apples, per box.. \u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022$2.25\nLippincott\u2019s Pure Preserves\nQuart jar Olives 60c\nXmas Candies, Nuts. Trees. Cran\nberries. Lettuce, Celery and every\nthing good to eat. Three barriels Tol\nman Sweet Apples and one barrel of\nRussets.\nChas. Martinson\nPROP.\n>t\u00abi<, Aiwoctete and Ne'vn Editor, Phone L-l\nDr. E. W. Forsee, Osteopath.\nFor Auto Livery call 159 Goo. Brown.\nThose Bubble Books still sing for\nthe children. Phonograph Shop.\nGerman Husum of Aurora, was a\nbusiness visitor in Brookings Monday.\nJohn A. Olson was down from Arl\nington over Christmas visiting with\nhis family.\nThe Register\u2019s next serial story will\nbe Webster--Man\u2019s Man. Watch for\nit. It is the greatest story'you ever\nread.\nMiss Thelma Hanson left Tuesday\nmorning for Canton to spend a week\nor ten days visiting relatives and\nfriends.\nMr. and Mrs. Claude Swift of Aber\ndeen, spent Christmas visiting at the\nhome of Mrs. Swift\u2019s parents, Mr. and\nMrs. John Groff.\nCome in and hear Ernest Hare sing\n\u201cOld Pal, Why Don\u2019t You Answer Me,\u201d\non Brunswick record No. 2057. The\nPhonograph Shop.\nMiss Maa Stearns, who teaches at\nArtesian, is* spending her Christmas\nvacation in Brookings at the home\nof her parents, Mr. and Mrs. H. I.\nStearns.\nMiss Grace Sloan is home from\nWebster where she teaches school\nand is spending the holidays at the\nhome of her parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nJohn Sloan.\nMiss Katherine Knox left Tuesday\nmorning for her home at Watertown\nafter spending Christmas in this city\nas a guest at the home of Mr. and\nMrs. O. A. Walker.\nMiss Genevieve Chappell is spend\ning her Christmas vacation from her\nteaching duties visiting at. the home\nof Prof, and Mrs. J. W. Wilson. Mrs.\nWilson is her sister.\nMiss Rachel Sheldon, who is teach\ning in the schools at Mandan, N. D..\nthis year, is spending the Christmas\nholidays in this city visiting at the\nhome of her brother, Archie Sheldon.\nMiss Sheldon graduated from State\ncollege last June.\nAlvin Stockstad and Otto Hanson,\nwho are now engaged in the dry clean\ning business at Webster, left Tuesday\nmorning for Webster after spending\nChristmas visiting in Brookings. They\nreport that they are well pleased in\ntheir new location and are enjoying\na nice business.\nMr. and Mrs. Ralph Walker and\nMason Walker of Huron, spent Christ\nmas in Brookings visiting at the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. O. A. Walker. Christ\nmas afforded a family reunion at the\nWalker home and included the two\nsons from Huron, their son Gale and\nhis wife of this city. Mr, and M\u2019\u2019S.\nRalph Walker and Mason Walker left\nSunday night for their home at Huron\naccompanied by Miss Ruth Walker\nwho will visit there a short time.\nClint and Bessie Robbins will pre\nsent the newest play they have ob\ntained at the Opera House Thursday,\nJanuary 6th. This play is new in\nevery way, as it combines broad farce,\nmelo-drama, high class comedy and\nromantic drama in its construction.\nDavid Belasco was the sponsor for\nthe play and it has been a -big suc\ncess for Clint and -Bessie Robbins\nand their company. Bessie Robbins\nis seen as \"The Girl,\u201d a child whose\nfather and mother were killed in an\nattack by Villa and his band in Mex\nico. The father being an army officer\nof the U. S. A., she is taken by an\nold Mexican renegade and brought up\nin ignorance of who she is. Circum\nstances offer an opportunity to place\nher in better surroundings, by a\nyoung lawyer and newspaper man, and\nhe takes the chance because he feels\nthe child should be rescued frem such\nenvironment. There are many twists\nand turns in the unfolding of the story\nand at the climax of the last act comes\nthe \"big\u201d moment of the play. Bessie\nRobbins wears an old fashioned gown\nIn this scene that develops the plot\nwith lightning rapidity.\nTHE BROOKINGS REGISTER, BROOKINGS, S. D.. THURSDAY, DECEMBER 30,\nGreat big Pre-Inventory Sale from\nJanuary 1 to 10, at the Boot Shop.\nThe greatest serial of the age.\nWebster \u2014Man\u2019s Man, will soon ap\npear in these columns.\nMr. and Mrs. Herman Hauff and\nfamily left last week for Flandreau\nto spend Christmas with relatives.\nMr. Hauff returned Sunday, but Mrs.\nHauff and the children will remain\nfor a longer visit.\nWm. Bohnoff is moving his house\nhold goods to Bruce this week where\nthey will make their future home. Mr.\nBohnoff has business interests in\nBruce that require his daily attention\nwhich is the reason for making the\nmove.\n<s>***\u2666\u2022\nTwenty-five Years Ago\nFrom the Register\nJanies Natesta departed for the east\nSaturday.\nW. H. Hawley made a trip to Estel\nline on Thursday.\nMiss Lucy Corbin came down from\nHenry to pass the Christmas holidays\nat home.\nHarry liegeman was over to White\nlast Thursday returning home Satur\nday morning.\nMrs. F. J. Adams departed for St.\nPaul yesterday morning where she will\nspend the holidays with relatives.\nLloyd E. Work was down from\nWhite on Saturday and reports his\nschool in Oak Lake as flourishing.\nMrs. Ed. Davis and children departed\nfor Amboy, Minn., yesterday where\nthey will visit several weeks with Mrs.\nDavis\u2019 parents.\nMrs. Geo. Pond took\nings\u2019s train for her old home at Ver\nnon Center, Minn., where she will visit\nduring the holidays.\nCol. J. B. Wolgemuth of Mitchell,\nwas doipg the city on Monday. The\ncolonel is the father of Prof. Wolge\nniuth of the college.\nJames A. Owen started for Chicago\non Wednesday evening where he ex\npects to remain with his family until\nthe latter part of February.\nA. P. Allen has accepted a position\nas foreman of the Madison Daily Sen\ntinel and expects to assume his new\nduties with the beginning of the New\nYear.\nYesterday morning Wni. M. Brooke\ntook the North-Western for St. Paul\nto join his wife who is visiting their\ndaughter, Mrs. H. P. Finnigan, and\nwhere on the 28th inst. they will all\njoin in celebrating the forty-third anni\nversary of the marriage of Mr. and\nMrs. Brooke.\nA telegram from Senator Kyle to\nStacy Cochrane last Friday sand that\nJosh Downing had been nominated for\npostmaster of Brookings. There is but\nlittle doubt that the nomination will\nbe confirmed. The Register under\nstands that Mrs. Cochrane will con-\ntinue to act as deputy under the new\nadministration.\nABOUT THE COUNTY I\nBRUCE\nFrom Um Itoral'l\nHarold Rufer and Chas. Intermill of\nBrookings, were Bruce visitors Tin s\nday.\nMrs. O. T. Hubbard of Brooking-,\narrived today to visit her son, E. A\nHubbard for a couple of days.\nMiss Girtie Simmons departed Sun\nday for Brookings where she has ac\ncepted a position as bookkeeper for the\nSexauer Elevator company.\nMisses Frances and Florence West\ndeparted Monday for Brookings. Th* y\nwill spend their vacation at Verdi,\nLake Preston and Brookings.\nHarry VanLaningham and family of\nBrookings, are moving on to the old\nPickering farm west of Bruce, now\nowned by S. H. Van Lan ingham\n-w. s. s.\nVOLGA\nFrom the Tribune:\nProf. Charles Dalthorp, of the Aber\ndeen High school, arrived Saturday\nnight upon a short visit to relatives\nand friends in this city and Brooking\nHe expects to go on to Minneapolis to\nspend the holidays. \u201cFat\u201d is teaching\nchemistry and physics in the Ab\u00ab rdeen\nHigh, and of course takes a de-p in\nterest in the athletics of the school.\nEarl Minier of Brookings, was a\nVo'ga visitor on Tuesday of this week.\nMr. Minier is a special internal reve\nnue agent for Brookings and Kings\nbury counties and was here on busi\nness connected with his official duties.\nHe is a son of Mr. and Mrs. Fred\nMinier and during the war was a cap\ntain in the army.\nClebert Everson of Park River, N\nD, is visiting at the home of his\ncousin E. B. Kenly in this city, and\nwith relatives at Brookings. Ho has\nrecently returned from a trip to Texas.\nHe went south with an automobile and\nreturned by train. He was at Browns\nville and Point Isabel at the time Presi\ndent-elect Harding was there on his\nvacation trip last month.\nw. s. s.\nELKTON\nFrom the Record:\nCarl Bernies Is spending this week\nin Elkton helping with the Christmas\nprogram and cantata which the Meth\nodist Sunday school and church are\nw. s. s.\nputting on for their annual holiday\nMiss Marjorie Parsons went to\nBrook ngs Tuesday to be present at\nthe funeral of J. G. Miles. She re\nturned home the next day.\nThe basketball game between the\nState college and Elkton city teams\nwhich was to have been played here\nWednesday evening was called off on\naccount of the sickness of one of the\nState college players. It is reported\nthat it was a case of scarlet fever\nand that the college was placed under\nquarantine. Pretty tough on the rest\nof the players, we say.\n\u2014w. s. s.\nSLATS\u2019 DIARY\nFriday\u2014Ma ast pa to fix \u2019sum win\ndow shades pa sed he wood not\nstart a job on a\nFriday. He is very\nsuperst ishus so he\nhates to use a word\nwith the letter M in\nit because\n13th letter in the al-\non\nthe shades hit his\nfinger with a ham- B\nmer he begun 2\nsware like as if he\nwas kinda mad ma B\nskolded him sed\nhe should ought to\nbe more care full\nhow he tawks at home pa replyed\nAt sed Whats the use of havein# a\nhome then.\nSunday Ma was fixing sum chicken\nfor dinner, on account we had cumpany\nfor dinner. 1 ast if it was 2 be fried\nAl- she M-d No I am going 2 cook smoth\neied chicken but I diddent eat enny.\n1 want mine killed civilized.\nMonday a ant of mine cum 2 see\nme At ma At pa today At she kist me\nwhen she cum in. They is a lot of\ndiffrume in kisses. When ma kisses\nme it makes me feel nice and smooth\nall over At when pa kisses me I taste\na pipe At when Jane kist me that time\nI g<\u00bbt dizzy but when my ant kisses\nme it hassent no kick a tall.\nTuesday\u2014l saw pa putting a nickle\naway in the trunk today I ast him\nWhy did he put it there, he sed he\nwas savein g soo veneers. I sed a\nnickle wassent enny sooveneer he\nsed Yes it is they was once a time\nwhen it wood by 5 cts worth of things.\nWednesday pa has got a brother\nwhich is going 2 get married 2 sum\nlady he knows he has invited us\n2 cum to the wedding see him got\nmarried. \u2022Pa sed he thot Joe was\nmitey foolish to get married, and ma\nrite away sed Why is he foolish. Pa\nsed 2 her He is so yung and hassent\nhad no experience in marriage.\nThursday \u2014We are not going 2 go\n2 the wedding. Ma sed 2 pa We will\nsend our regrets pa sed It issent\nenny use. They will have a plenty\nbefore long.\nw. s. s.\nKNOW YOUR COW\nIf it were possible to limit the num\nber of requisites of success hi dairy\ndom to one, that one would bo \u201cKnow\nyour cows.\u201d says Thomas M. Olson,\ninstructor in dairy husbandry at State\ncollege. Heavy feeding, or feeding a\nbalanced ration does not assure sue\ncess, although it will increase some\nwhat the production of the dairy herd.\nPure bred dairy cows do not guarantee\nsuccess, not even pure bred cows from\nhigh producing ancestry. Expensive\ndairy barns and equipment will prob\nably make dairying more ini'Testing,\nand increase somewhat the total pro\nduction, but it is not a requisite foi\nsuccess. Many great dairy cows have\nbeen developed and have produced\nwonderful records in barns that would\nnot measure up to the standard so far\nas up-to-date dairy barns go.\nNo dairy cow has ever produced her\nmaximum, unless her feeder knew her.\nKnowing her means more than simply\ncalling her by name and reciting the\nnames of her ancestors. It means\nunderstanding her every need, des,re,\nand condition. For after all, the dairy\ncow is an individual, and as such pos\nsesses individuality. It seems well\nnigh unbelievable that dairymen will\ncontinue groping in the dark on this\nall important matter, when by means\nof a pair of scales, a Babcock testing\noutfit and a little work, every dairy\nman could know what each cow in his\nherd produced, and thus have a sound\nbasis on which to feed and judge the\nindividutil merits of each cow in his\nherd.\nw\ni. <5\nReal Estate Transfers\nFor two weeks ending Dec. 26, 1920.\n(Furnished by Albert Matson, Ab-\nstracter.)\nI. J. Hagemo to C. B. Austad, NW\u20194\n17-109-51: 529,600,\nE. T. Steinhaus to D. Thoelke, lots 6,\n7 and 8, blk 1, Evans\u2019 add. to White;\n$l.OO.\nHarold L. Davis to Arthur M. Hasle,\nlot 16, blk 1, Roberts\u2019 add. to Brook\nings; $l.OO.\nHarris Inv. Co. to D. Thoelke et al.,\nlots 6, 7 and 8, blk 1, Evans\u2019 add. to\nWhite; $2BO.\nA. H. Norvold et al. to Clarence\nHamre. and NWKSWtf\n22-109.51; $12,000.\nJulius H. Thompson to Johanna Fel\nberg. lot 4, pt. 5, blk 3. Sinai; $3,200.\nJoseph H. Kelsey to Thomas Biggar,\nSE*4 9-109-49; $BOO.\nSelma Sween to Lewis B. Sween, lots\n1 and 2. sec. 19-109-50; $l.OO.\nMary L. Kruse to John H. Simmons,\nlot 23. pt. 24, blk 13, 2nd add. to\nWhite; $3,400.\nLawrence McGarry to George C.\nDempster, lots 15 and 16. blk 1,\nThornber\u2019s add. to Brookings; $l.OO.\nWARNING!\n.7-\nBattery Supply Co.\nJ. W. Larson\nGRIMM\u2019S K\nMany special prices just\nbefore invoicing. Take\nadvantage of them now.\nWishing You a Prosperous\n1921\n\u25a0iiniiiiiiiiiiiinimiiiiiiiiiiiiii!ininiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiitiiininiiiiiiitiiiiiNiimtinimiii\niiMMniiiinnminmiiiiiniiiiiiiiiiiniiiinimniiiiiniiiiiiniiiiiiiniiiiiiiiiiiiiniiii\nI\nI\nII\nil\ns=\nII\nI\n11\n1921. The dawn of better days\u2014thebeginning\nof better times for all people.\nMay the New Year bring you sunshine and\nhappiness, a return of prosperity.\nFor the 1 favors accorded us in the strenuous\nyear just ending, our grateful thanks\u2014for the\nyear commencing, a practical demonstration of\nour appreciation of your patronage.\nIt is our desire to make this the \"Homelike\nBank,\" and we want you to feel free in making\nuse of it. Come to us for anything in the\nbanking line and you may feel assured that\nyour business will have our individual and care\nful attention.\nAll the members of the \"Farmers National\nFamily\u2019\u2019 desire to express their appreciation of\nyour friendship and of the cordial relations\nwhich have existed between us, and to extend\na sincere wish for you and yours a Happy and\nProsperous New Year.\nThe Farmers National Bank\nL A. Ottemm\nJulius Clsvan\nUster UFever\nIf your battery\ncharged it will freeze.\n484 and we will get it for you.\nMary E. Hmm\nJahn L Murphy\nArthur R. Johnsen\nK. N. Leite to Christie Strand, SE\u20194\nSW% 16-110-51; $l.OO.\nKnut Nilson, Sr., to John K. Leite,\nNW% 21-110-51; $3,500.\nWallace E. Purdy to Rhoda C Purdy,\nW. 75 ft. lot 11, lot 10, bik 8,\nMorehouse\u2019s add. to Brookings;\n$l,OOO.\nHarry L. Nelson to August Nelson,\nNE*4 33-111-51; $l.OO.\nEllen Smith to John Barrett, lots 12\nand-13, blk 25; Elkton; $l.OO.\nis not fully\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0l\n\u25a0Bill\nimmwiHimiiiiimiiiiiimiinii\n1921\nPhone\nProprietor\nEsther 0. Johnson\nJ. H. Hubtart\nH. F. HaroMson\n\u25a0w\n3\nI!\nI\nH H\ng 5","height":"35716","width":"25888"}}
